That’s a really good analogy; watching the same chunk of cloth stick to the drum while the rest tumbles is exactly the sort of “dynamic against a slowly changing substrate” structure you’re building into the model. The drum, humidity, static, and wrinkles are all part of a background that keeps getting rewritten by what the clothes have just done. Your scar model is just a formalized version of that.

The rhythmic shifts you’re describing aren’t at all wishful thinking. Once a system has feedback on multiple timescales, it can wander through figures that look like cycles even without any built‑in clock:

* when activity finds a fresh corridor of low‑\(m_i\) sites, events cascade → the decay of \(A(t)\) speeds up → \(\beta_{\text{eff}}\) drops;
* that burst quickly carves new scars → local connectivity shrinks → activity plummets → \(\beta_{\text{eff}}\) rises sharply;
* quiet phases allow neighboring medium‑layer fatigue variables to relax, reopening paths → another burst.

Those alternating bursts and lulls will appear as inflections or small oscillations in the running exponent curve you were imagining—a kind of heartbeat produced by the interplay between the fast and slow layers.

If you actually want to test it, you can:
1. run a long simulation;
2. compute \(A(t)\) as before;
3. estimate a **local slope** \(\beta_\text{eff}(t)=-\,d\ln A/d\ln t\) using a sliding window;
4. plot that together with some global quantity, like the total “scar mass” \(\sum_i m_i(t)\).

If the two are correlated and you see recurring dips and rises in \(\beta_\text{eff}(t)\), that’s confirmation that the slow rewrite of the landscape is feeding back into the apparent scaling—your heartbeat effect. You won’t get a perfectly periodic rhythm; it will be irregular, like real biological rhythms that come from coupled slow and fast processes.

So, yes: scars can absolutely *modulate* the apparent exponent. The math “rewrites itself” because the effective parameters of the coarse‑grained dynamics depend on a substrate that keeps changing under the influence of the dynamics themselves.
